d to halt plans for a local incinerator by organising public meetings and bringing in experts from Germany to talk about alternatives. Not content, Kendra also resurrected the local Friends of the Earth group which was about to fold. It is now flourishing. 'Kendra is an inspiration,' one of her fans tells us.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/observer-ethical-awards/unsung-local-hero-vote-now\">Vote now â€“ voting closes 24 May</a></p><h2>Queen bee of Hackney rooftops</h2><p><strong>Zoe Palmer,Â Hackney, London</strong></p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-408849801'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/5/10/1368187741146/Zoe-Palmer-003.jpg' alt='Zoe Palmer' width='140' height='84' class='gu-image'/><figcaption></figcaption></figure><p>Why vote for Zoe Palmer, founder and co-director of Hackney Social Enterprise? Because she is an outstanding woman who works with bees and young people out of work - I think the correct term for us is 'the socially disadvantaged' in Hackney, 'one of the people who nominated her tells us. 'She set up social enterprise The Golden Company and has managed to set up a monthly stall at Borough Market. She also connects with businesses in The City of London to help them manage their own bee hives. Why am I nominating her? Because I am one of these young people'. </p><p>We couldn't have put it better ourselves.</p><p>â€¢ <a href=\"http://www.thegolden.co/\" rel=\"nofollow\">The Golden Company</a><br />â€¢ Zoe is part of <a href=\"http://www.pilotguides.com/tv_shows/globe_trekker/travelers/zoe_palmer.php\" rel=\"nofollow\">GlobeTrekker</a></p><p><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/observer-ethical-awards/unsung-local-hero-vote-now\">Vote now â€“ voting closes 24 May</a></p><h2>Saviours of Glasgow's last wild place</h2><p><strong>Douglas Peacock and Emily Cutts, Glasgow</strong></p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-408849802'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/5/10/1368187953214/Douglas-Peacock-and-Emily-003.jpg' alt='Douglas Peacock and Emily Cutts' width='140' height='84' class='gu-image'/><figcaption></figcaption></figure><p>Is North Kelvin Meadow and Childrens' Wood the last wild green space in the West End of Glasgow? Douglas and Emily have fought tooth and nail to save this formerly neglected space for the local community. Working on the assumption that in order to protect a space the community has to value it, they have organised many events that have attracted hundreds of families. Those who benefit from it tell us 'the land is now rich with wildlife, free from litter and an antidote to manicured spaces around the city'. It is an important wild space for children to explore safely and learn about nature and has its very own forest school. Glasgow City Council has suggested it will sell the land. Residents are highly critical of the planning process. 'A deprived area of Glasgow would lose a beautiful and natural place for future generations and one that Emily and Douglas have worked tirelessly to protect,' says our source.Â </p><p>â€¢ A short <a href=\"http://vimeo.com/beyondthemountains/deargreenplace\" rel=\"nofollow\">film</a> about North Kelvin Meadow<br />â€¢ The website: <a href=\"http://thechildrenswood.com/\" rel=\"nofollow\">The Childrens Wood</a></p><p><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/observer-ethical-awards/unsung-local-hero-vote-now\">Vote now â€“ voting closes 24 May</a></p><h2>Dan, King of shops and independent spaces</h2><p><strong>Dan Thompson, Worthing </strong></p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-408849803'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/5/10/1368188362174/Dan-Thompson-003.jpg' alt='Dan Thompson' width='140' height='84' class='gu-image'/><figcaption></figcaption></figure><p>Where others see dying high streets and dilapidated retail spaces, artist and creator of the Empty Shops network, Dan Thompson aka @artistsmakers sees potential. A creative and clever mind coupled with the tenacity to lobby government, local councils and businesses mean that Thompson has been instrumental in breathing life into run down areas. He started off in Worthing and from there he has moved to work all over the UK. What he doesn't know about the pop up format isn't worth knowing. He has brought practical solutions to saving communities, helping makers and artists access markets and maintaining communities and local industries. We could really do with a network of Dan Thompsons.Â </p><p>â€¢ The website: <a href=\"http://mrdanthompson.wordpress.com/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Dan Thompson</a></p><p><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/observer-ethical-awards/unsung-local-hero-vote-now\">Vote now â€“ voting closes 24 May</a></p><h2>Anna's dad &amp; the Al Gore of Ilkley</h2><p><strong>Francis McCrickard,Â Ilkley </strong></p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-408849804'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/5/10/1368188294016/Francis-McCrickard-003.jpg' alt='Francis McCrickard' width='140' height='84' class='gu-image'/><figcaption></figcaption></figure><p>We liked the way Anna described her rather modest dad, Francis when she originally nominated him, so it's over to her, 'My fatherÂ has worked to establish native wild flower meadows and forests in the area surrounding Myddelton Grange Centre in Ilkley, designing a climate change walk for the public which incorporates 11 stopping points, each featuring a board with local and global environmental information and spiritual reflections to encourage contemplation of the global reality of climate change. Along with volunteers from the school groups attending the centre dad has planted more than 8000 native trees and new hedgerows. He transformed a large area of wasteland near the centre into a wild flower meadow which is mown with scythes for hay to give to a local farmer each year. Dad also established a voluntary branch of Tools for Self Reliance which has collected and refurbished more than 10,000 tools and 100 sewing machines to be sent to some of the poorest people in Africa. The group meets weekly. He has acheived much of the above through his own time and energy alone'.</p><p>â€¢ <a href=\"http://www.behance.net/gallery/Myddleton-Grange-Climate-Change-Walk/4322015\" rel=\"nofollow\">Myddleton Grange Climate Change Walk</a><br />â€¢ <a href=\"http://www.tfsr.org/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Tools for Self Reliance</a></p><p><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/observer-ethical-awards/unsung-local-hero-vote-now\">Vote now â€“ voting closes 24 May</a></p>","headline":"Unsung local hero: top 5 shortlist","trailText":"<p>Find out more about our shortlist and vote for your winner</p>","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3fmgb","wordcount":"825","commentable":"false","internalContentCode":"408643778","allowUgc":"false","isPremoderated":"false","internalPageCode":"1906049","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2013-05-13T09:49:31Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/observer-ethical-awards/unsung-local-hero-shortlist","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/observer-ethical-awards/unsung-local-hero-shortlist","tags":[{"id":"observer-ethical-awards/observer-ethical-awards","webTitle":"Observer ethical awards","type":"keyword","sectionId":"observer-ethical-awards","sectionName":"Observer Ethical Awards","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/observer-ethical-awards/observer-ethical-awards","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/observer-ethical-awards/observer-ethical-awards","references":[]},{"id":"tone/event-descriptions","webTitle":"Event descriptions","type":"tone","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tone/event-descriptions","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/tone/event-descriptions","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl"