cal Awards","webPublicationDate":"2013-01-18T17:09:24Z","sectionName":"Observer Ethical Awards","sectionId":"observer-ethical-awards","id":"observer-ethical-awards/welcome-2013-observer-ethical-awards","fields":{"secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/01/07/Welcome-140x84.gif","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3d4z9","standfirst":"Ethical living columnist and awards founder, <strong>Lucy Siegle</strong>, introduces the 2013 Observer Ethical Awards","hasStoryPackage":"false","lastModified":"2014-05-21T13:50:54Z","body":"<figure data-media-id='gu-image-405198282'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/1/15/1358268897069/Lucy-Siegle-003.jpg' alt='Lucy Siegle' width='140' height='140' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Our ethical living columnist and awards founder, Lucy Siegle joins us as chair of the judging panel</figcaption></figure><p>Welcome to the 2013 Observer Ethical Awards in association with Ecover. Back in 2005 when Annie Lennox joined us on stage to give out our first crop of Ethical Awards I'm not sure any of us realised how big a deal the awards would become. Since then we've become known (rather gratifyingly) as the \"green Oscars\", assessed thousands of entries and secured some of the biggest cultural and scientific movers and shakers around as judges (page 29 lists our extraordinary roll call of judges this year). Our generous sponsor, Ecover, has handed out thousands of pounds' worth of bursaries to support the next generation of young green champions. But the awards we launch today are our biggest celebration of environmental and social justice yet. They reflect the fact that over eight years the ethical landscape of the UK has broadened and deepened. </p><p>The UK is home to a magnificent spectrum of people and businesses who get it: sustainability doesn't happen by magic just as resource depletion doesn't just go away; it takes human effort and ingenuity to make life more ethical. Voting opens today so that you can reward that effort. The Observer has a longstanding affiliation with both environmental and social justice. It's notable that EF Schumacher, the economist now regarded as the founder of ethical living, worked through many of his ideas for how to live within ecological parameters while writing in the pages of the Observer. The awards are built on this foundation, but you don't require similar green heritage to enter, or to be working on a big scale. You may know of a potential winner operating on a very local scale indeed.</p><p>This year we're on the lookout for an <strong>unsung local hero</strong>, while through our <strong>well dressed</strong> category we want to celebrate the person who has got to grips with their own wardrobe, crowning the king or queen of ethical style in the UK. New for 2013, we are championing products and services with undeniable ecological intelligence, rewarding those that could prove to be a game changer on a small or large scale, making it easier for us to be ethical in every day life. And for the first time we're also looking for nominees in the <strong>travel</strong> industry. We're honouring those who prove travel can be world-changing in a positive way and that our wanderlust can have an ethical dividend. This is the year for the next generation of ethical agitators to step forward. We know our <strong>young green champions</strong> are not willing to sit around and wait to inherit a ruined planet so tell us what they are doing â€“ ï¿¡6,000<sup>1</sup> is on offer for the under-18s who have the best ethical project for 2013. For the first time we're also rewarding the teacher or supervising adult and their family who dedicate time and effort to making these ideas a reality. </p><p>Over eight years you have supported the awards process and our panel of judges by <a href=\"https://secure.easyanswer.net/ethicalawards\">voting and nominating</a> with great gusto. We need you to <a href=\"https://secure.easyanswer.net/ethicalawards\">vote and nominate</a> again with the same commitment and enthusiasm. We don't mind if you vote altruistically or because there are great prizes for voters. The end result is that between us, by June, we will have uncovered the brightest and best people, projects, campaigns and businesses making sure that we have an ethical future.</p><p><strong><sub><sup>1</sup>The winning project receives Â£6,000 in three annual Â£2,000 instalments. Instalments are paid subject to an annual project appraisal and agreed spending plan between the winner an Ecover.</sub></strong></p>","headline":"Welcome to the 2013 Observer Ethical Awards","trailText":"<p>Find out about the 2013 Observer Ethical Awards from our ethical living columnist and awards founder, Lucy Siegle</p>","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/01/07/Welcome-140x84.gif","wordcount":"585","commentable":"false","internalContentCode":"402432863","allowUgc":"false","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Lucy Siegle","internalPageCode":"1853775","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2013-01-18T17:09:24Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/observer-ethical-awards/welcome-2013-observer-ethical-awards","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/observer-ethical-awards/welcome-2013-observer-ethical-awards","tags":[{"id":"observer-ethical-awards/observer-ethical-awards","webTitle":"Observer ethical awards","type":"keyword","sectionId":"observer-ethical-awards","sectionName":"Observer Ethical Awards","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/observer-ethical-awards/observer-ethical-awards","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/observer-ethical-awards/observer-ethical-awards","references":[]},{"id":"tone/event-descriptions","webTitle":"Event descriptions","type":"tone","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tone/event-descriptio